  "prompt": "What is the difference between a beta particle and an electron?",
  "response": "A beta particle and an electron are actually very closely related, but there are some subtle differences:\n\nBeta Particle:\n1. Specifically refers to an electron emitted during radioactive decay\n2. Produced when a neutron in an unstable atomic nucleus is converted to a proton\n3. Always carries a negative charge\n4. Originates from within an atomic nucleus during nuclear decay\n5. Has high energy and is typically emitted at high velocity\n\nElectron:\n1. A fundamental subatomic particle found in atomic orbitals\n2. Part of the normal atomic structure around the nucleus\n3. Always carries a negative charge\n4. Found orbiting atoms in electron shells\n5. Has a constant rest mass and charge\n\nKey Similarity:\n- Both beta particles and electrons have exactly the same mass and charge\n- The primary difference is their origin and context of emission\n\nIn essence, a beta particle is essentially an electron, but one specifically produced through radioactive decay of an atomic nucleus, while an electron is a more general term for the negatively charged particle found in atomic structures.",
